<script lang="ts">
	import Introduction from './components/Introduction.svelte';
	import ReflectionQuestions from './components/ReflectionQuestions.svelte';
	import AssessmentCriteria from './components/AssessmentCriteria.svelte';
	import CustomSection from './components/CustomSection.svelte';
	import { getSdgColor } from '$lib/utils/sdg-colors';

	interface Props {
		sdgColor?: string;
	}

	let { sdgColor = getSdgColor(12) }: Props = $props();
</script>

<div class="lesson-content">

	<CustomSection title={"The Body of a Better World: A Dance & Movement Exploration"} content={"<strong>(30-60 MINUTES)</strong>"} {sdgColor} />

	<CustomSection title={"Materials:"} content={"<p>Audio<br>Open space suitable for movement<br>Whiteboard or large chart paper<br>Markers<br>Notebooks or paper<br>Pens/Pencils</p>"} {sdgColor} />

	<Introduction content={"<p>Begin with a clear explanation of guided imagery.<br>Explain that it’s a technique where the facilitator uses descriptive language to guide participants to visualize specific scenarios, sensations, or emotions.<br>Emphaisze that the goal is to tap into the mind-body connection and explore these visualizations through movement.<br>Highlight that there are no “right” or “wrong” ways to move, and encourage students to interpret the imagery in their own way.<br>Lead a brief, simple guided imagery exercise to introduce the concept:<br><em>Example:</em>\n<ul>\n<li>Close your eyes and soften your gaze. Imagine you are standing in a forest. Feel the soft earth beneath your feet. Breathe in the fresh, clean air. Notice the dappled sunlight filtering through the leaves. Move as if you are a tree, swaying gently in the breeze. Reach your arms up towards the sky, like branches growing. Feel your roots grounding you to the earth.”</li>\n</ul><br>Facilitate a short discussion:\n<ul>\n<li>What images came to mind during the exercise?</li>\n<li>How did the imagery influence your movement?</li>\n<li>How can guided imagery help us explore complex ideas and emotions?</li>\n</ul><br>Introduce or reintroduce Global Goal 12: Responsible Consumption and Production, and emphasize the urgency of addressing unsustainable consumption patterns and the need for a shift towards more sustainable practices.<br>Briefly review the key targets and indicators of Global Goal 12 if needed.<br>Facilitate a class discussion:\n<ul>\n<li>What are some of the biggest challenges related to consumption and production in our society?</li>\n<li>How does our individual consumption contribute to global issues?</li>\n<li>What are some examples of sustainable alternatives to current practices?</li>\n</ul><br>Engage students in a discussion about how guided imagery can be used to explore themes of consumption and production. Ask questions like:\n<ul>\n<li>How can we use guided imagery to visualize the consequences of unsustainable practices?</li>\n<li>Can guided imagery help us embody the concept of a circular economy or sustainable lifestyle?</li>\n<li>How can movement be a powerful tool for expressing our concerns and hopes for a sustainable future?</li>\n</ul></p>"} />

	<CustomSection title={"Guided Imagery and Movement Exploration"} content={"<p>Lead the students through a series of guided imagery exercises, each focusing on a specific aspect of Global Goal 12.<br>Provide clear and evocative instructions, encouraging students to interpret the imagery through movement.<br>Use a variety of movement qualities (e.g., flowing, sharp, fast, slow) and spatial patterns (e.g., circular, linear, expansive, contracted) to enhance the experience.<br>Incorporate elements of breathwork to connect movement with emotional expression.<br>Examples of Guided Imagery Sequences:\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Target 12.1</strong> <em>(Sustainable Consumption and Production Patterns):</em> Imagine you are a policy being created. Fee the energy of collaboration and planning. Move with a sense of purpose and direction. Now, imagine this policy being implemented across a country. Feel your movement expand and reach out to different communities. Imagine the positive changes resulting from this policy: reduced waste, cleaner production. Feel your movement become smoother, more harmonious. Imagine a world where all countries are working together for sustainable consumption and production. Move with a sense of unity and global connection.</li>\n<li><strong>Target 12.2</strong> <em>(Sustainable Management of Natural Resources):</em> Imagine you are a tree in a forest. Feel your roots grounding you, your branches reaching for the sky. Move with a sense of strength and stability. Now, imagine the forest being cut down. Feel your movement become restricted, diminished. Imagine the land being restored, new trees being planted. Feel your movement become hopeful, regenerative. Imagine a world where we use resources wisely, respecting the balance of nature. Move with a sense of reverence and care.</li>\n<li><strong>Target 12.3</strong> <em>(Food Waste):</em> Imagine you are a seed, growing into a plant, producing food. Feel the energy of growth and abundance. Move with a vibrant, flourishing quality. Now, imagine that food being wasted, thrown away. Feel your movement become heavy, discarded. Imagine systems being upt into place to prevent food waste, sharing food with those in need. Feel your movement become purposeful, compassionate. Imagine a world where no food is wasted, and everyone has enough to eat. Move with a sense of gratitude and justice.</li>\n<li><strong>Target 12.4</strong> <em>(Environmentally Sound Management of Chemicals and Waste):</em> Imagine you are a chemical, moving through the environment. Feel your potential to be helpful, to create. Move with a sense of purpose and control. Now, imagine that chemical becoming toxic, polluting the air and water. Feel your movement become chaotic, destructive. Imagine systems being put in place to safely manage chemicals and waste. Feel your movement become organized, responsible. Imagine a world where chemicals are used safely, and waste is minimized. Move with a sense of care and stewardship.</li>\n<li><strong>Target 12.5</strong> <em>(Substantially Reduce Waste Generation):</em> Imagine you are a piece of clothing, being used and discarded. Feel the cycle of consumption and waste. Now, imagine being recycled, transformed into something new. Feel your movement become circular, resourceful. Imagine a world where waste is minimized, and everything is reused. Move with a sense of innovation and creativity.</li>\n<li><strong>Target 12.6</strong> <em>(Encourage Companies to Adopt Sustainable Practices):</em> Imagine you are a company. Feel the pressure to produce and sell. Move with a driving, ambitious quality. Now, imagine becoming a sustainable company, valuing people and planet. Feel your movement become more responsible, ethical. Imagine companies being transparent and accountable for their impact. Move with a sense of integrity and leadership.</li>\n<li><strong>Target 12.7</strong> <em>(Promote Sustainable Public Procurement):</em> Imagine you are a government agency, making purchasing decisions. Feel the weight of responsibility. Move with a deliberate, organized quality. Now, imagine choosing sustainable products and services. Feel your movement become more ethical, foward-thinking. Imagine public spending supporting a sustainable economy. Move with a sense of vision and commitment.</li>\n<li><strong>Target 12.8</strong> <em>(Ensure Information and Awareness for Sustainable Development):</em> Imagine you are a piece of information, spreading awareness about sustainable practices. Move with a light, flowing quality, reaching out to others. Imagine people learning and changin their habits. Feel your movement become more connected and impactful. Imagine a world where everyone is informed and empowered to make sustainable choices. Move with a sense of hope and possibility.</li>\n<li><strong>Target 12.a</strong> <em>(Supporting Developing Countries):</em> Imagine you are technology being shared between countries. Feel the potential for positive change. Move with a collaborative, supportive quality. Imagine developing countries using this technology to build sustainable systems. Feel your movement become empowering, transformative. Imagine a world where technology is a tool for global sustainability. Move with a sense of partnership and progress.</li>\n<li><strong>Target 12.b</strong> <em>(Sustainable Tourism):</em> Imagine you are a traveler, experiencing a new place. Feel the wonder and excitement. Move with an adventurous, curious quality. Now, imagine tourism harming the environment or exploiting local culture. Feel your movement become cautious, respectful. Imagine sustainable tourism, benefiting both travelers and local communities. Move with a sense of responsibility and connection.</li>\n<li><strong>Target 12.c</strong> <em>(Rationalize Inefficient Fossil-Fuel Subsidies):</em> Imagine you are fossil fuel being used to power our lives. Feel the energy and power. Move with a strong, driving quality. Now, imagine the harmful effects of fossil fuels, the pollution and climate change. Feel your movement become destructive, unsustainable. Imagine a transition to renewable energy, clean and sustainable. Feel your movement become hopeful, regenerative. Imagine a world powered by clean energy. Move with a sense of change and progress.</li>\n</ul><br>Throughout the exercises, encourage students to:\n<ul>\n<li>Listen to their bodies and move in a way that feels comfortable and expressive.</li>\n<li>Connect with the emotions and sensations evoked by the imagery.</li>\n<li>Explore different ways of interpreting the visualizations through movement.</li>\n</ul></p>"} {sdgColor} />

	<CustomSection title={"Creative Movement Exploration"} content={"<p>After the guided imagery sequences, facilitate a brief period of free movement exploration. Invite students to:\n<ul>\n<li>Reflect on the images and sensations they experienced during the guided imagery.</li>\n<li>Explore their own movement responses to the themes of consumption and sustainability.</li>\n<li>Move in a way that feels authentic and expressive.</li>\n</ul><br>Provide prompts or suggestions if needed to guide the exploration:\n<ul>\n<li>How would you move to represent the idea of excessive consumption?</li>\n<li>Can you show through movement the concept of reducing waste?</li>\n<li>How can you express your hope for a sustainable future through your body?</li>\n</ul><br>Lead a gentle cool-down to bring the energy back down and prepare for reflection.<br>Include stretching, deep breathing, and calming movements.<br>Facilitate a class discussion:\n<ul>\n<li>What was your experience with the guided imagery and movement exploration?</li>\n<li>What images or sensations were most powerful for you?</li>\n<li>How did the movement help you connect with the themes of Global Goal 12?</li>\n<li>What did you learn about your own relationship with consumption and sustainability?</li>\n<li>How can movement and creative expression be used to advocate for change?</li>\n</ul></p>"} {sdgColor} />

	<CustomSection title={"Reflection and Summary"} content={"<p>Have students reflect on their learning experience through writing or discussion.<br>Ask guiding questions like:\n<ul>\n<li>How did the guided imagery and movement exploration help you connect with the concepts of responsible consumption and production on a deeper, more embodied level?</li>\n<li>What sensations or emotional shifts did you experience in your body as you moved through the different visualizations related to Global Goal 12?</li>\n<li>Did physically embodying concepts like resource depletion, waste transformation, or sustainable practices offer you new insights that words alone might not have?</li>\n<li>What did you learn about the power of your own body and imagination to explore complex global challenges?</li>\n<li>How can connecting with these issues through movement make them feel more real or urgent?</li>\n<li>What new insights did you gain about Global Goal 12 and the importance of sustainable consumption and production patterns through this movement activity?</li>\n<li>How did the different guided sequences (e.g., imagining a forest being cut down, or a product being recycled) illuminate the challenges and opportunities within specific targets of Global Goal 12?</li>\n<li>Did the activity make you think differently about your own daily consumption habits and their impact on the planet?</li>\n<li>What common themes or powerful messages about sustainability emerged from our collective movement exploration?</li>\n<li>How does a holistic understanding of consumption and production, as explored through movement, relate to the broader goals of a sustainable future?</li>\n<li>Did any particular movement sequence or visualization resonate with you on a personal level, perhaps sparking a new commitment to sustainable practices?</li>\n<li>What emotions did you connect with during this lesson, and how might those emotions motivate you to take action related to Global Goal 12?</li>\n<li>What is one key takeaway about responsible consumption and the power of creative expression that you will remember from this lesson.</li>\n<li>What is one specific action, big or small, that you feel inspired to take after this lesson to contribute to achieving Global Goal 12?</li>\n</ul></p>"} {sdgColor} />

	<CustomSection title={"Assessment"} content={"<ul>\n<li>Consistent and mindful involvement in all phases of the lesson, including the initial guided imagery exercise, subsequent movement explorations, and participation in class discussions.</li>\n<li>Comprehension of Global Goal 12, targets and core concepts. This will be evidenced through the intentions and interpretations conveyed in movements and verbal contributions during the discussion.</li>\n<li>Originality and expressiveness in translating abstract or descriptive imagery (e.g. “chemical becoming toxic,” “resource flowing) into physical movement.</li>\n<li>How clearly and powerfully the movements communicated the understanding of specific aspects of Global Goal 12. Did the physical expression successfully evoke thought or emotion related to the goal?</li>\n<li>Willingness to experiment with and apply different movement qualities (e.g., flowing, sharp, heavy, light, expansive, constricted) to enhance the meaning of their interpretations.</li>\n<li>Nuance and insight demonstrated in reflections, particularly concerning the role of embodied learning in understanding global challenges and the complexities of sustainable consumption patterns.</li>\n</ul>"} {sdgColor} />

</div>
